Onion routing is a way to protect your online privacy by sending messages through multiple servers, each adding a layer of encryption like an onion’s layers. Each server only knows the previous and next step, not the whole path, making it very hard to trace the original sender or message content. This method hides your identity and activity from spies or attackers watching the network. It’s used in privacy-focused tools and networks. Key ideas to explore include “anonymous routing,” “multi-layer encryption,” “Tor network,” and “hidden services.” It makes tracking or spying on communications much harder.